  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Transfer duty -- also called stamp duty -- is a state government tax payable when you acquire property in Queensland. For downsizers selling a long-held family home and buying something smaller, it can be a genuinely material cost that affects the financial logic of the move. It is also an area where a lot of people have mistaken beliefs about what concessions are available, particularly around whether anything specific exists for older Australians or people downsizing.</p>

      <p>The short answer: as of 2026, Queensland does not have a dedicated transfer duty concession for downsizers or seniors. There is no QLD equivalent to the Commonwealth Downsizer Contribution scheme (which is a superannuation measure, not a transfer duty one). What does exist are general concessions that apply based on how you use the property you are buying, and understanding those is essential if you want to minimise your duty bill when purchasing your next home.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How Queensland transfer duty rates work</h2>
      <p>Transfer duty in Queensland is calculated on the higher of the purchase price or the market value of the property. The rates are progressive -- you pay a lower rate on the first portion of the value and higher rates as the purchase price rises. For a home purchased at $1,000,000, the general rate duty (without any concession) is calculated on a sliding scale and will be in the range of $38,000 to $40,000. At $1,500,000, the duty liability without a concession rises to approximately $66,000.</p>

      <p>These are material numbers. For someone selling a home they bought for $300,000 thirty years ago and buying something at $1,200,000, the duty on the purchase is a real factor in how much of their sale proceeds they actually have available.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The home concession: what it actually covers</h2>
      <p>The most significant concession available to Queensland buyers is the home concession. This applies when you are buying a property that you intend to use as your principal place of residence. To qualify, you must move into the property within one year of settlement and you must not have owned a home in Queensland in the three years before the purchase that you also used as your principal place of residence (or, if you did own one, you must have sold it).</p>

      <p>The home concession reduces the rate of transfer duty you pay. On a $1,000,000 purchase, the home concession reduces the duty payable from approximately $38,000 to approximately $21,500. That is a saving of around $16,500. On higher-value purchases, the concession saves proportionally less in percentage terms but remains significant in absolute dollars.</p>

      <p>For downsizers, the home concession is typically the relevant concession, and most will qualify provided they have sold their previous home and intend to move into the new property. The key point is that you cannot hold onto your old property and claim the concession on the new one -- you need to have disposed of the previous home to satisfy the eligibility requirements.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The first home concession: not relevant for downsizers</h2>
      <p>The first home concession provides a further reduction in duty for eligible first home buyers and is not available to people who have previously owned a home in Queensland. Downsizers will not qualify for this concession.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Is there a specific downsizer or senior concession in Queensland?</h2>
      <p>No. As of 2026, Queensland does not have a specific transfer duty concession for downsizers, retirees, or older Australians. This is a common misconception, and one that occasionally leads to unpleasant surprises when people realise the duty bill is larger than they expected. If you have heard that Queensland has a seniors concession on transfer duty, that information is not accurate as it applies to property purchases. Pensioner card holders and seniors may be eligible for certain other state government concessions (such as utility rebates), but these are unrelated to transfer duty.</p>

      <p>The Commonwealth Downsizer Contribution -- which allows people aged 55 and over to contribute up to $300,000 each from the proceeds of selling their home into superannuation -- is a federal measure and has nothing to do with state transfer duty. It is a useful financial planning tool for eligible sellers, but it does not reduce the duty payable on your next purchase.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How downsizers can structure their purchase to reduce the duty bill</h2>
      <p>Given that no specific downsizer concession exists, the most effective strategies for managing transfer duty when downsizing are structural. The first is simply timing: ensure you have sold your existing home before buying the new one, so you can claim the home concession on the purchase without any doubt about eligibility.</p>

      <p>The second is considering what you are buying. Transfer duty applies to the full purchase price of the property. If you are moving from a large family home to a smaller apartment or a low-maintenance property at a materially lower price point, the duty bill on the purchase will be correspondingly lower. Buying at $700,000 rather than $1,200,000 is a duty saving of roughly $20,000 to $25,000 on its own, which can be a relevant factor in property selection for buyers who are cost-conscious.</p>

      <p>The third consideration, for eligible buyers, is whether the property being purchased is a house and land package where the land is being separately transferred. In some new build situations, the duty is calculated on the land value rather than the combined house and land value, which can produce a lower duty outcome. A solicitor or conveyancer can advise on whether this structure is available and appropriate for your situation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The interaction with capital gains tax when downsizing</h2>
      <p>Transfer duty and capital gains tax are separate obligations. Most people selling a home that has been their principal place of residence for the entire period of ownership will be exempt from capital gains tax under the main residence exemption. But transfer duty is payable on the purchase side regardless of the CGT position on the sale.</p>

      <p>For people who own an investment property and are considering downsizing into it -- moving from their current home into a property they have been renting out -- both the CGT and transfer duty implications need to be carefully thought through. The main residence exemption is not available for periods the property was used to produce rental income, which means a partial CGT liability may apply on an eventual sale. A tax adviser can work through the numbers for your specific situation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why sellers who are also buying need to plan ahead</h2>
      <p>For anyone selling one property and buying another simultaneously or in close sequence, factoring the full cost of the purchase into the financial planning is essential. Transfer duty is often underestimated in the budget, particularly when prices have risen from the last time someone bought property. A home purchased in Brisbane's inner east at $1,500,000 will attract duty of around $66,000 even with the home concession applied. That is a meaningful line item that needs to be in the budget alongside legal fees, moving costs, and any renovation or improvement work.</p>

      <p>Leaving transfer duty out of the calculation -- or assuming there is a concession that does not exist -- is one of the more common planning errors people make when downsizing. Getting accurate numbers from a solicitor or the Queensland Revenue Office before you commit to a purchase price range will give you a much clearer picture of what you can actually afford after all costs.</p>

